However, the application of dielectric capacitors is currently limited by their low energy density, especially in applications requiring large capacitances and small packaging size. For example, the best-performing commercial dielectric capacitor, biaxially oriented polypropylene (BOPP), only has an energy density of ~1–2 J cm−3, which is an order of magnitude lower compared to commercial electrochemical capacitors (20–29 J cm−3)6,7. Therefore, achieving high energy density in dielectric capacitors is a major bottleneck in extending their practical applications. The recoverable energy storage (Urec) for dielectric capacitors is generally described by the following equation: Urec = ∫EdD, where E and D are electric field and displacement, respectively. Specifically, for linear dielectrics, Urec =  ∫EdD=12DE=12ε0εrEb2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
